snippet.authorDisplayName: It's A Me, Dat Random Dick Butt
snippet.textDisplay:
TL;DR:

A kids "confidence" doesn't need to be measured in "status symbols" at that early of an age. This fvcking r-tarded sneakerhead culture needs to be purged from the gene pool. I consider myself a practical man. I myself only own 14 pairs (2 pairs for a day in the week) of quality rubber shoes (because I need to from being worn out) and to that I have 4 more additional (2 pairs of genuine leather (1 black, 1 dark tan, and 1 light brown}for formal events all regularly polished with shoe shine after use, a 1 steel toe boot)}} all immediately sent to a my patron shoe repair show on the first sign of damage))) and 2 ye olde trusty slippers and 1 croc under for those dirty jobs around the house all under a thousand dollars. I know I know, they need to flaunt opulence because they are frequent seen in public and need to keep their reputation up as befits stars of their caliber in their respective industry but in this economy? That's just fvcked up, stupid even!

With that being said, I just want to share with you the wisdom of Macklemore in his song Wing$:
[ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gAg3uMlNyHA ]
And I quote:
"...
We want what we can't have, commodity makes us want it
So expensive, damn, I just got to flaunt it
Got to show 'em, so exclusive, this that new shit
A hundred dollars for a pair of shoes I would never hoop in
Look at me, look at me, I'm a cool kid
I'm an individual, yea, but I'm part of a movement
My movement told me be a consumer and I consumed it
They told me to just do it, I listened to what that swoosh said
Look at what that swoosh did. See it consumed my thoughts
Are you stupid, don't crease 'em, just leave 'em in that box
Strangled by these laces, laces I can barely talk
That's my air bubble and I'm lost, if it pops
We are what we wear, we wear what we are
But see I look inside the mirror and think Phil Knight tricked us all
Will I stand for change, or stay in my box
These Nikes help me define me, but I'm trying to take mine, off
..."

Food for thought.
